# Source of truth for runtime dependencies (what gets installed on the server).
# Edit this file, NOT requirements.txt.
#
# Regenerate the hashed requirements.txt after editing:
#     ./venv/bin/pip-compile --allow-unsafe --generate-hashes --resolver=backtracking requirements.in
#
# `--allow-unsafe` is the opt-in to pin pip + setuptools alongside the
# rest. The flag's name is legacy and misleading -- it has nothing to do
# with security; pip-tools historically considered the bootstrap layer
# "unsafe to pin" because doing so could deadlock pip's own source-build
# machinery against itself. With wheel-only installs and modern pip,
# pinning these is fine and is the only way deploy.sh (which runs
# `pip install --require-hashes -r requirements.txt`) keeps the venv's
# pip current and CVE-free over successive deploys. Without this flag,
# every fresh CVE in pip itself stays unpatched on the VPS until someone
# remembers to ssh in and run `pip install --upgrade pip` by hand.
#
# Dependabot also regenerates requirements.txt automatically on version-bump
# PRs (it detects the .in -> .txt pip-tools pattern; it preserves the
# --allow-unsafe flag from the existing requirements.txt header).

# pip is the install tool, not an import. It's listed here so deploy.sh's
# `pip install --require-hashes -r requirements.txt` keeps the venv's pip
# at the lockfile-pinned version, hash-verified, on every tag deploy.
# Without this line, pip-compile skips it (no runtime dep references it),
# the lockfile carries no pip pin, and pip on the VPS drifts behind
# whatever was installed at server-setup time -- which is how the
# CVE-2026-3219 era of pip persisted on the droplet.
